elstone, Somerset, England","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England"},"cs":{"about 1129–":"okolo 1129–Zesnulý","1159–Female":"1159–Zesnulá","1129–Male":"1129–Zesnulý","1129":"1129","1215":"1215","1159":"1159","about 1129":"okolo 1129","1224":"1224","Cothelstone, Somerset, England":"Cothelstone, Somerset, Anglie","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1129–":"omkring 1129–Afdød","1159–Female":"1159–Afdød","1129–Male":"1129–Afdød","1129":"1129","1215":"1215","1159":"1159","about 1129":"omkring 1129","1224":"1224","Cothelstone, Somerset, England":"Cothelstone, Somerset, England","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England"},"nl":{"about 1129–":"circa 1129–Overleden","1159–Female":"1159–Overleden","1129–Male":"1129–Overleden","1129":"1129","1215":"1215","1159":"1159","about 1129":"circa 1129","1224":"1224","Cothelstone, Somerset, England":"Cothelstone, Somerset, England","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England"},"en":{"about 1129–":"about 1129–Deceased","1159–Female":"1159–Deceased","1129–Male":"1129–Deceased","1129":"1129","1215":"1215","1159":"1159","about 1129":"about 1129","1224":"1224","Cothelstone, Somerset, England":"Cothelstone, Somerset, England","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Russell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: of Norman origin, from Old French and Anglo-Norman French <i>r(o)ussel</i>, a diminutive of Old French <i>rous(e)</i> ‘red, reddish’, used either as a nickname for someone with red hair or a ruddy complexion, or as a personal name. Compare   Rouse  . This Norman name has been established in Ireland since the 12th century. It has been reinforced in Britain and Ireland by Huguenot bearers of the name <i>Roussel</i>, of the same Old French origin.","English: habitational name from any of several places called Rushall (Norfolk, Staffordshire, Wiltshire) or possibly sometimes from Rusthall in Speldhurst (Kent). Rushall in Staffordshire derives from Old English <i>rysc</i> ‘rush, rushes’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’. Rushall in Norfolk derives from an uncertain first element + Old English <i>halh</i>. Rushall in Wiltshire derives from an Old English personal name <i>Rust</i> (genitive <i>Rustes</i>) + <i>halh</i>. Rusthall in Speldhurst (Kent) probably derives from Old English <i>rust</i> ‘rust, rust color’ + <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’, but with a change in the final element due to influence from Middle English, Old English <i>hall</i> ‘hall, residence’, perhaps referring to a nearby building.","Americanized form of German <b>Rüssel</b>, from a pet form of any of various personal names formed with the element <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’."],"variants":[{"name":"Russler","meanings":["German (<b>Rüssler</b>):","occupational name for a farmer, from an agent derivative of <i>rüsseln</i> ‘to shallow plow’.","variant of <b>Rüssel</b> (see   Russell   2)."]},{"name":"Rouse","meanings":["English: nickname for a person with red hair or a ruddy complexion, from Middle English, Anglo-Norman French <i>rous(e)</i> ‘red(-haired)’ (from Latin <i>russ(e)us</i>).","Americanized form of German   Raus  .","Walloon and northern French (<b>Rousé</b>): variant of <b>Rosé</b> (see   Rose  )."]},{"name":"Russel","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Russell  .","German: from a pet form of <i>Russ</i>, see   Russ   2.","northwest German (<b>Rüssel</b>): probably a variant of   Rossel  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":86,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":95,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Russell was born about 1129, in Berwick, Dorset, England. He had at least 1 daughter. He died in Cothelstone, Somerset, England."},"et":{"about 1129–":"umbes 1129–Surnud","1159–Female":"1159–Surnud","1129–Male":"1129–Surnud","1129":"1129","1215":"1215","1159":"1159","about 1129":"umbes 1129","1224":"1224","Cothelstone, Somerset, England":"Cothelstone, Somerset, England","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England"},"fi":{"about 1129–":"noin 1129–Kuollut","1159–Female":"1159–Kuollut","1129–Male":"1129–Kuollut","1129":"1129","1215":"1215","1159":"1159","about 1129":"noin 1129","1224":"1224","Cothelstone, Somerset, England":"Cothelstone, Somerset, England","Berwick, Dorset, England":"Berwick, Dorset, England"},"fr":{"about 1129–":"environ 1129–Décédé","1159–Female":"1159–Décédée",